In Java, a `byte` value is signed, so its range is from -128 to 127.  
As opposed to a range of 0 to 255.

There are two approaches you can take.  I&#39;ll demonstrate both.

As a solution, you can reduce your check value, on line 13, of `count &lt; 255` to 127.  
For added persistence, you can use `Byte.MAX_VALUE`.

```java
if (nextByte == currentByte &amp;&amp; count &lt; 127) {
    count++;
} else {
    os.write((byte) count);
    os.write((byte) currentByte);
    count = 1;
}
```

Or, you can bit-mask your `count` value in the `decompression` method.

```java
count = currentByte &amp; 0xff;
```

This will return positive values for negative `byte` values.  
For example.

```java
-1 &amp; 0xff == 255
```

Additionally, as a recommendation, you can reduce both your `compress` and `decompress` methods.

Place the `compress` contents within a try-finally block.  
That way, you can close your streams in the event of an `IOException` occurring.  
And, increase the scope of `nextByte`, by bringing its declaration outside of the `while` loop.

```java
public static void compress(InputStream is, OutputStream os) throws IOException {
    try {
        int currentByte = is.read();
        int nextByte;
        int count = 1;
        while (currentByte != -1) {
            nextByte = is.read();
            if (nextByte == currentByte &amp;&amp; count &lt; 255)
                count++;
            else {
                os.write((byte) count);
                os.write((byte) currentByte);
                count = 1;
            }
            currentByte = nextByte;
        }
    } finally {
        os.flush();
        is.close();
        os.close();
    }
}
```

As for the `decompress` method, same situation, place the contents within a try-finally block.  
Your `currentByte` assignment can be placed within the `while` condition statement.  
And, you can utilize the `Arrays.fill` method to populate the `bytes` array.

```java
public static void decompress(InputStream is, OutputStream os) throws IOException {
    try {
        int currentByte;
        int count, value;
        byte[] bytes;
        while ((currentByte = is.read()) != -1) {
            count = currentByte &amp; 0xff;
            value = is.read();
            bytes = new byte[count];
            Arrays.fill(bytes, (byte) value);
            os.write(bytes);
        }
    } finally {
        os.flush();
        is.close();
        os.close();
    }
}
```

As an added measure, just to demonstrate what&#39;s happening when assigning a value greater than 127 to a `byte`.  
Consider the following, we&#39;ll start at 125 and increment by 1, 4 times, to get to 129.

```java
byte value;
String binary;
for (int count = 1; count &lt; 5; count++) {
    value = (byte) (125 + count);
    System.out.printf(&quot;+%d, &quot;, count);
    System.out.printf(&quot;value= %4d, &quot;, value);
    binary = &quot;%8s&quot;.formatted(Integer.toBinaryString(value));
    binary = binary.substring(binary.length() - 8);
    System.out.printf(&quot;%s%n&quot;, binary);
}
```
